<section xml:id="sec_factoring_expressions">
  <title>Factoring Expressions</title>
  <p>
    Maple can also factor expressions with the <c>factor()</c> command. It will factor polynomials (including those with multiple variables)
    and will even factor more complicated expressions (like those involving trig functions as seen below).
    <idx><h>factor</h></idx>
  </p>
  <console prompt="> ">
    <input>factor(x^2 - 1);</input>
  </console>
  <p>
    <me>
      \displaystyle  \left( x-1 \right)  \left( x+1 \right)
    </me>
  </p>
  <aside>
    <p>
      In some cases, Maple may factor the expression and perform some additional basic simplification.
    </p>
  </aside>
  <console prompt="> ">
    <input>factor((x^2 + 2*x - 15)/(x^2 + 7*x + 10)</input>
  </console>
  <p>
    <me>
      \displaystyle  \frac{x-3}{x+2}
    </me>
  </p>
  <console prompt="> ">
    <input>factor(sin(x)^2 - 3*sin(x) + 2);</input>
  </console>
  <p>
    <idx><h>mathematical functions</h><h>sine</h></idx>
    <me>
      \displaystyle  \left( \sin \left( x \right) -1 \right)  \left( \sin \left( x \right) -2 \right)
    </me>
  </p>
  <aside>
    <p>
      If Maple cannot factor the expression given, it will output the original expression.
    </p>
  </aside>
  <console prompt="> ">
    <input>factor(x^2 + 1);</input>
  </console>
  <p>
    <me>
      \displaystyle {x}^{2}+1
    </me>
  </p>
  <p>
    Maple will factor expressions with multiple variables as well. Be sure to include multiplication (*) between variables.
  </p>
  <console prompt="> ">
    <input>factor(a^3 + 3*a^2*b + 3*a*b^2 + b^3);</input>
  </console>
  <p>
    <me>
      \displaystyle (a+b)^3
    </me>
  </p>
</section>